			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Nice grandstanding.
<br />

<br />
This article dripped with disdain for the military and was relatively offensive to me.
<br />

<br />
Leon's legal gymnastics are entertaining. His insistance that the military's willingness to use reliable information, even if gained via torture is tantamount to the military admitting to torture is assinine. Aside from the nebulous definition of what constitutes torture, I have yet to see any evidence of systemic abuses of interrogation technique at Gitmo that would constitute torture. Until a full review is complete there, I will continue to believe that if it was occurring, it was isolated to a few individuals as in Abu Garib and that those individuals will be punished accordingly. At that point we come back to the question of whether or not to use the information gathered through their nefarious efforts. The military says yes, if it is reliable information. Meaning, that such information can be corroborated via other sources. Normally that means several other sources. Let me give you and example of the military way of thinking when we judge the worth of a peice of information. In the anti-submarine warfare world we have several levels of confidence in our information. The lowest being that our information means nothing, the highest meaning we see it with our own eyeballs. Anything in between although possible or probably requires mitigating circumstances of serious nature for us to act upon. Even if a submarine shoots a torpedo at us, we still classify it as simply "probably" as submarine and then only if certain other criteria are met, can we shoot back. I won't go into all the reasons why we do this shit, but in large part it is due to a mindset molded during Vietnam that leaves every action we take open to armchair generaling by the likes of use board ranters. So when the military says reliable information, you cannot assume it means the same thing as when the government or intelligence community say reliable information. Perhaps in light of the failings of our intell community in the last decades and our governments utter inability to see through it, better oversight will follow and that will foster a military like discipline to the way they handle their craft. Perhaps not. Either way I will continue to give the Marines in Gitmo the benefit of the doubt.
<br />

