				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">You are trying the same mental gymnastics as Leon. It does not work.
<br />

<br />
The inability to use information gained from torture is not the detterant to illegaly torturing prisoners. Imprisonment is. As stated before, the line between valid interogation technique and torture is a fine one and apparently very easy to cross. Perhaps making those definitions a little stricter would help. But disregarding information completely, even when confirmed by other means, because it was initially elicited via torture is stupid. That is what the military is saying. How you twist that to mean anything else is beyond me. 
<br />

<br />
We are not allowed to hand over to, or extradite prisoners to countries where torture is legal. This remains against the law, so I am unsure how that relates to this situation at all. If one of these nations however, imprison someone we want and subsequently torture them for information and hand that information or prisoner to us, I still see no issue as it pertains to use of the information or continued imprisonment as long as the information provided is both reliable and pertinent. 
<br />

<br />
The issue of other nations torturing prisoners is not a military or legal issue to the US. It is a diplomatic issue handled by both the State Department and our ambassador to the UN. Disregarding information provided by these nations, whatever they did to obtain it is stupid as well.
<br />

<br />
Our current administration is doing enough to trash our worldwide credibility. We cannot afford to become a hear/see/speak no evil nation in a world where evil exists. 
<br />

<br />
Forbidden fruit? Don't be sophomoric. I get enough of that at work.
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
