				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Because the information gained from torture is notoriously unreliable? Using non credible testimony to imprision people isn't an American moral value, dude. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You are making statements not applicable to the argument. The military has stated that the information must be reliable and verifiable. That means it must be available via other means or other sources. So your assertion of information from torture being unreliable holds no water, at least as it pertains to this argument.
<br />

<br />
This has nothing to do with who is being tortured. But the blind eye approach to information gained in any way is as abhorent to me as the torture itself. The military argument here in no way supports the use of torture. It simply accepts the fact that even under the best circumstances it can happen at a U.S. military facility and under normal circumstances happens elsewhere. There are procedure and policy in place to keep it from happening, but we don't live in a perfect world. 
<br />

<br />
Your view seems to be, that admitting information gained via torture either legally in some other country or illegally here, would lead to a system of us simply using other nations to detain our prisoners in hopes that they will torture out of them the information we need, or lead to a legalization or sweeping under the rug or torture in our prisons. Now, I certainly am not blind to human nature, but I don't have that much disdain for my fellow Americans to think that either would be allowed. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Once again, gaining information through torture is neither reliable nor an American moral value. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Niether is killing people, it is against our moral value and in fact is illegal. Yet we are comfortable sending our young men and women around the world to just that and hell we as a people overwhelmingly, if not stupidly, allow our government to administer this ultimate punishment for certain crimes, yet it is against our moral value. My point here, is that you are trying to paint this picture in black and white, when it is much more complex. I do not accept that the ends always justify the means, I do accept that sometime this is so.
<br />

<br />
It is funny that someone who leans left like yourself could tip so far on any issue like this that your eyes close from the force of gravity. There are definitely instances where information from a tortured prisoner should be disregarded, especially if that torture deals with the prisoners guilt or innocence or the guilt of another suspect / prisoner. On the other hand, there is a great deal of information that should not be disregarded, what you suggest is that we disregard everything they say, unless they are sitting on a couch watching Oprah and volunteer it. That shit just isn't going to happen. 
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
