			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Too many people are trying to make whether torture is right or not the argument. That is not the question. Everyone here agrees that torture is abhorrent. But as abhorrent as it is, ignoring information gathered by it, is just as wrong. 
<br />

<br />
We have laws against torture. We prosecute violators of these laws. What the military is saying, is that they will continue to punish those who torture prisoners. They are also saying, that if the information gained from that torture is valuable, reliable and verifiable, they will act upon it. That is it. They would be stupid not to.
<br />

<br />
Remember the last time you beat up your brother for fucking your cousin-wife? When told you she had started an allotment from your check to his bank account during the ass beating, you used that information right? Same thing skippy.
<br />

<br />
The lawyers in this case are dancing around a couple issues. One I agree with, one I do not. I agree with using, and acting upon verifiable testimony no matter how it was extracted. What was not said, but has been implied by many here, is that, some of this information may be used as incriminatory against the prisoner him or herself as confession statements whether verifiable or not. Neither side so far has been clear with that actual accusation or a response to it. Of course it is implied by the military in the statement that normal rules of evidence to not apply nor do these prisoner enjoy the basic rights of American citizens. However it is being rightfully challenged in the courts as we speak. 
<br />

<br />
The title of the thread and the initial post pre-suppose that the military are blood thirsty thugs who are out to get confessions no matter how we do it and that since we are ok with using statements ellicited by torture that we must neccissarily support the use of torture. But of course we are not the real blood thirsty thugs, we are the naive pawns of the dastardly Bush administration. 
<br />

<br />
Resorting to obfuscation by emotionalizing the situation doesn't help either. Leewei was not advocating terrorizing the world by randomly torturing folks for information. He  was saying that ignoring the information, no matter how it was attained is as criminal as the act itself. Suppose Israeli intelligence operatives tortured the plans for 9/11 out of some terrorists and passed it along to us. Should we ignore that information, because it was torture based? If Sgt. Joe Schmukatelli of CID beats a confession out of a suspected terrorist who then implicates his wealthy cousin in Boston in a future plan, should we ignore that information and not check out that cousin, after we sent Sgt. Joe to courts martial?
<br />

<br />
Torakus</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
