			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Fucking Invalid Sessions. Kiss my ass. 
<br />

<br />
I wrote a huge response to ya Relbeek. But apparently your board's attention span is only so long.
<br />

<br />
I agree fully that the line between interrogation and torture needs to be more clearly defined. In fact I said so in an earlier post in this thread. However, throwing the baby out with the bath water is not a very good replacement for it. 
<br />

<br />
The "how many must we torture" response to the ticking time bomb is a slightly less interesting diversion, since nobody is advocating it. I can only think you are trying to deflect the issue to a question of our right to hold them without charge, a discussion we have had already several times on this board. Its not the issue.
<br />

<br />
The military is simply saying, that we are realists. We do not live in a perfect world and bad things are going to happen. As much as we abhor torture, it is going to happen. What we are not going to do, is ignore the information gained, but at the same time we are going to continue to uphold the laws against it.
<br />

<br />
Some seem afraid that this will lead to a culture of torture since we can use the information from it. It has not, it will not. Information that is reliable, verifiable and coroborated can and should be used, even as evidence against the prisoner. 
<br />

<br />
Torakus</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
