			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It's interesting that information gained by a law enforcement officer by illegal interrogation or illegal search and seizure is inadmissable (as it should be) as evidence anywhere</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Well I don't fully agree with those laws either. Obviously there must be some protection against illegal search and seizure. There are not police police, so these types of protections must hold them in check. But if I slapped the shit out of Jeff Dahmer and he subsequently 'fessed up to his murders, I would be severely dissapointed in our justice system letting him off the hook.
<br />

<br />
I guess I just look at it as a matter of degrees. I am comfortable with the ends justifying the means in a lot of things, especially when it relates to things like terrorism. I wish our world were all fluffy clouds of chocolate pudding and whipped cream, where a stern admonishment would deter criminals from committing crimes and terrorist from committing acts of terrorism. But this world I have to live in is a bit harsher. Certainly I do not advocate violent interrogation or physical abuse. There are other means. Unfortunately in the care bear world we are trying to create, even putting a prisoner in a mentally fatiguing situation is called torture. Hell some of the things I went through as initiation rites are worse than what these guys suffered in Gitmo (and of course are now strictly forbidden since the pussification of military rites of passage began).
<br />

<br />
Tora</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
