			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Curiously, I'm in agreement with Relbeek in arguing that testimony extracted under duress should remain inadmissible in court.
<br />

<br />
It's too much of a temptation for a police officer to get lazy...why investigate a crime when you can simply grab the first person you see and beat a confession out of him?  We've seen it happen in other countries many, many times.
<br />

<br />
I'm not going to elaborate too much more lest I start having flashbacks to "The Untold Story"...a Hong Kong movie based on a true story dealing with a serial killer and his capture by the Taiwan police.  /shudder.  The frightening part of the movie, aside from levels of graphic violence that make The Passion of the Christ look like a Teletubbies episode, is that you leave the movie wondering whether the serial murderer or the cops are worse.
<br />

<br />
On the other hand, there do exist certain rare situations where I think rubber-hosing someone --or worse-- is the only morally responsible choice.  For example, if there was a bomb or other terrorist attack being planned and you have someone in custody who you are certain is involved, then you get the information out of the guy any way you can to save innocent lives.
<br />

<br />
It's an ugly moral and ethical dilemma and I'm not sure that blind platitudes from either side are going to resolve it.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
