			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Seven?
<br />

<br />
Seven was not nearly as bad.  But Seven also lacked the social message of The Untold Story.  
<br />

<br />
Take the OMG ICK factor of Seven, triple it, and add the sort of morally-ambiguous message Reservoir Dogs left you with, only about doubled.  That's a pretty good starting point to imagine how appalling a movie The Untold Story is.  You'll walk away from it wanting to take a shower...and then you'll remember its a true story.  Then you'll probably want a stiff drink and a shower.
<br />

<br />
Seven was about "Oooh!  Look at the creepy psycho-killer-guy and the crazy stuff he does...and oh, yeah, you can empathize with the Brad Pitt character at the end when he faces a moral crisis."
<br />

<br />
The Untold Story is just orders of magnitude worse.  You see "Ooh, look at the creepy Psycho guy and the not-so-totally crazy stuff he does...then there's the cops who are just as bad if not worse...and ooh, ick, you get to empathize with BOTH of them."
<br />

<br />
And, truthfully, the graphic violence is far worse than in Seven.  Far, far worse.
<br />

<br />
It won the Hong Kong equivalent of the Academy Award for Best Picture when it was released.  And it earned it.  You'll walk out of it feeling like a sledgehammer hit you in the gut.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
